   <abstract >In this thesis, we will provide a Finslerian point of view on several objects of classical informationgeometry. Therefore we will generalize the Fisher-Rao metric to a family of Finsler metrics which we denote by ??-Fisher-Rao metrics. Generalizing a construction of Khesin et al. we construct a simplifying transformations, that allows us to derive an explicit formula for geodesics on Dens(? ) and that reduces the geodesic problem on Prob(? ) to finding geodesics on an ??-sphere. We then show that the Amari-Chentsov connection on the space of all positive densities can be interpreted as the Chern connection of the ??-Fisher-Rao metric and we also show that this equivalence does not hold on the space of probability densities. For the space of densities we can use this correspondence to calculate the flag curvatures of the ??-Fisher-Rao metric and show that they are identically zero. Next if we restrict ourselves to the case of manifolds of dimension one, we can provide a new geometric interpretation of the non-periodic Proudman‚ÄìJohnson equations as geodesic equations of the right invariant homogeneous ? 1,?-Finsler metrics on the diffeomorphism group. We then show that in the non-periodic case two families of equations, the generalized inviscid Proudman‚Äì Johnson equation, and the ?-Hunter‚ÄìSaxton equation (recently introduced by Cotter et al.) coincide for a certain range of parameters. Generalizing a construction of Lenells for the Hunter‚ÄìSaxton equation [57], we analyze these equations using an isometry from the diffeomorphism group to an appropriate subset of real-valued functions. Thereby we show that the periodic case of the ?-Hunter-Saxton equations is equivalent to the geodesic equations on the ??-sphere in the space of functions, and the non-periodic case for both the ?-Hunter-Saxton and the inviscid Proudman‚Äì Johnson equations is equivalent to a geodesic flow on a flat space. This allows us to give explicit solutions to these equations in the non-periodic case, and answer several questions of Cotter et al. regarding their limiting behavior. Finally we derive the geodesic equation of a right invariant Orlicz norm on the diffeomorphism group Diff(?1).</abstract>
